Fully present and aligned with my life’s mission through healing and art finally in my happy place. I have begun the transition of moving to Trinidad and opportunity has graciously flowed onto my path. I am working on a project that I cannot wait to share with you all in the upcoming weeks! It’s quite funny how the Universe works. As a child, I always wanted to call Trinidad home, now I can. I have to fly to Boston every three months for the next 2-5 years to be screened for cancer, in between I will be here on my abundantly ever giving tropical island. It has been one hell of a year fighting through cancer. Through pain, confusion, trauma, and victory life is blossoming quite lovely. A testimony indeed. This arrangement is from Kenny, our gardener on property. All flowers are grown in our backyard! What a beautiful gift and warm welcome home. I love nothing more than divine flowers. A colorful arrangement as Monet and Renoir would paint in vase paired with Victorian elements of a custom fretwork arched hallway. Happy weekend, friends from Trinidad & Tobago 🇹🇹! One love. Tend to your garden.🤍💐

Three weeks ago, I still needed assistance walking. Last year up until Christmas Eve, I was in the hospital for my 5 day cycle of treatment. By the end of every infusion I would be passed out from how strong these toxins are. Then in need of wheel chair assistance to Dad’s vehicle —only to rest and be up at 7am to get back to the hospital and do it all over again. There are endless side effects of chemotherapy, one of them is severe headaches. It would feel as if my brain was getting electrocuted but I had no choice but to bare the pain. I would have to take a “brain test” called the “animal test” where I’d name off as many animals as I was able within one minute before chemo. “Advark, Agouti, Antelope” ..I’d always start with those three. Ifosfamide, an alkylating agent used in cancer treatments was one of five different chemotherapy drugs I had to take, it can cause neurotoxicity and memory loss. “Chemo Brian” is what some doctors use as a term commonly used to describe thinking and memory problems that a patient with cancer may have before, during, or after cancer treatment. I am now 7 months out of treatment and still experiencing chemo brain. I’m taking out two spoons to eat with for breakfast guys! I have headaches every week. Thinking and speaking is just different. Yet, I’ve been blessed with an early Christmas gift..my legs are getting stronger! I’m no longer having to walk up stairs leaning onto walls or a banister for support. I’m moving slowly but I’m moving. I started working with @kwesipaulthomas6545 @tkb_totalkickbox this week and I’m elated to be able to ease my way back into fitness. Learning new techniques and strategies is forcing me to work my brain by getting into the rhythm of functioning outside of survival mode when I was getting treatment. If you’re struggling this holiday season I wish you hope, light, positivity and support! I realized I had an entire team at the hospital caring for me and once you get out of treatment if you’re lucky, you’re thrown back into this world. I’m slowly building my team of wellness back together and learning how to navigate life after cancer. Make time for your wellness and your mental. Island love to all🌺

What a year! I’m so thankful for your friendship today and every day.

Bonjour 2023–what a facked up year (and 10 months) it has been fighting through cancer. My mental, physical, and spiritual were in a constant battlefield. My life will never be the same. I still have another year of recovery but I have breath. I’m alive. 

Me? Cancer? Never. So, we all think. Ewing’s —What? Ewing’s Sarcoma? I’m going to lose my left eye to a disease I have never heard of? How will I paint? How many? 2 years —left to live? I surrender. 

Invasive surgeries, 49 chemotherapy sessions, 32 radiation treatments, 5 blood transfusions, lost the magical gift of naturally conceiving, facial paralysis, a blood thrombus in my heart and osteonecrosis. It’s been hell. A year plus of pain, trauma and being lead by faith. 

I beat cancer! Your support played a significant role in helping me win this battle. I’m so grateful for our community here around the world! Truly, I would have been lost without your encouragement. 

New is the year, new are the hopes, new is the resolution, new are the spirits, and new are my warm wishes just for you. Have a peaceful, creative, restful, adventurous and healthy New Year! As you pursue your art, hopes and dreams, may this chapter bring you much success and may your journey be wonderful despite the difficulties. Thank you for inspiring me to do my best this past year.

Cheers to another blessed year of taking on the world together, flowing forward in our boat of inner wisdom. 🧿

It’s luck, it’s genes, it’s complete mystery. Our time on this planet is ticking, so why not live while we’re here? I mean truly LIVE. Be present. Let’s treat our body with kindness and shower those who support us in times of illness, injury, grief and recovery with immeasurable unchanging love. Make the time to face your inner demons, relationship with your self, and paint your life the way you wish to live. I believe we’re all artists in some fashion or another. Sharing this moment I filmed last year when I was crawling through an ablaze fire, called Ewing’s Sarcoma cancer. It’s been a ride but I’m learning to set healthy boundaries that is needed for my recovery. Peace of mind is everything to me. Moments connecting with nature in quietness, listening to the wind’s whisper through de coconut trees is my morning medicine. We’re almost a week healing into this new chapter. Have a safe, spontaneous, creative, meditative and lovely weekend beautiful souls. I’m off to painting and heading out this eve to dance some pain away under the moonlight. Caribbean love and island sunshine from Trinidad!
First landscape painting of 2023 in progress

The message of the night was love. Through Soca music under the stars and moonlight we danced, we celebrated life. Oh, just for a short little journey we have here together on this planet. I’m an artist recluse by nature and was awkward in crowds before cancer, so it took a lot of courage to step outside of the house. But I did it! I packed my essential oils in my purse and took breaks from the crowds when I needed to. The leggies held up well! Great is the art form. Positivity of oneness left everyone in the crowd with a smile. Island vibes! There’s something special about that synonymous creative feel good energy that is contagious. Indigenous sounds from our ancestors vibrated through our spirits surrounded by lush green mountains.

The sounds of our ancestors resonated within our spirits last night during the Panorama Semi-Finals taking place in the historic Queen’s Park Savannah. Steel pans (steel drums) were created right here on the Caribbean island of Trinidad in the 1930s. Steel pan history can be traced back to the enslaved Africans who were brought to the islands during the 1700s. There is no sweeter sound than pan! This is the start of Carnival! 🥁🇹🇹 Congratulations to every band who made it to this round, a grand achievement! Big up to Uptown Fascinators on placing 1st with Collin Lucas’ Dollar Wine arranged by Ojay Richards. Post-cancer life healing on my favorite island, Trinidad. The pixie has returned! There is no other country in the world that heals me the way Trinidad & Tobago does through its diverse cultural history, delicious eats, sweet music, art, writing, fruit, natural waters and land. 🤍

Trinidad, you healed me in so many ways. You will always be the hands that hold my heart. Oh how I miss those coconut trees, green mountains, buss up roti and talkari, pan concerts, Cuevas waves, island sun, new compadres and fluffy friends. 

Well, I’m back in Boston and there are no coconut trees. We have snow folks! I had my six month scans last week. 

Leading up to my appointments, I had a few scares where I thought I saw something growing on my face. Just as easily as the tumor prior appeared on my left zygomatic bone nearly 2 years ago, paranoia lingered. There’s no pretty way to put this, cancer is not pretty. It strips you from your body parts and some of us our fragile life. I vomited bile and had no appetite, my nerves were shot. 

A few days later it was a long day at the hospital, triggering in every way rolling through those same halls. My legs gave out at the end of the day so a thoughtful nurse grabbed a wheel chair. I felt defeated that I couldn’t walk out of the hospital with confidence. Disappointed that my independence has been forced to still be dependent because of cancer. 

Yet I am fortunate, lucky and beyond grateful to still be here with both of my legs! Chemotherapy toxins are strong enough to kill all rapid growing cells including all cells of your hair, stomach lining, bone marrow, eyes, nails, and heart tissue. 

Healing takes time. Post-cancer healing takes its own special healing time. A healing where you cannot put a time stamp on. However, I will put a time stamp on cancer! Praise God, I am still in remission existing in this impermanent vessel. Six month scans —CLEAR!!!

This #WorldCancerDay, I remind you to advocate for yourself by acting now to detect cancer earlier, check your body for lumps or discomfort so you can diagnose it faster, treat it better and give your loved ones/yourself the hope of a cancer-free future. 

I was thriving in my late 20’s living in Laguna, California when a painful lump appeared on my face. I had over 15 different appointments with male doctors who laughed sharing that I wasted my time coming in, “just go home and heat compress your face. You’re healthy, in shape and young. You will be fine. Oh, hunny that is a sebaceous cyst, I’m not even going to run an x-ray. Are you sure you’ve never had face filler? Maybe it’s botched filler in your face.” I had to advocate for myself. I would answer almost feeling as if I had to defend myself by answering, yes, actually I’m fully aware I never had filler. As a single female going to majority of my doctor appointments alone, I was left with no answers, completely humiliated and had a painful growing tumor on my cheekbone. I never in my years saw cancer in my cards. Had I not been an advocate for my body and health I could quickly have lost my left eye or my life.

 I eventually was diagnosed with an aggressive children’s cancer, stage II Ewing’s Sarcoma. The Oncologist team in California had never treated anyone with this type of cancer. After my friend’s mother made a miracle call to get me into Dana Farber, I packed up my life in one week and moved to Boston to be treated by an oncologist who specializes in pediatric cancers. 

I had zero idea of what horrifying journey was ahead of me. None of us do. 49 chemotherapy treatments, surgeries, 32 radiation treatments, 5 blood transfusions. Some of us don’t make it out alive from this rigorous treatment.

 Cancer is nasty, it is unforgiving. If you have lost someone close to cancer. I am sorry. I will do everything in my power to help spread awareness of this horrible disease! If you are a warrior yourself—let us celebrate our battle and our brothers and sisters we have lost along the way. Holding all in prayer, comfort, and hope today! 🙏💫🎗

Our Fathers are like the bark of a tree that gives supply to the tree to sustain it.

As you mark your diamond jubilee birthday, I just want to say that diamonds really are a gal’s best friend. You are more than a father, you are my reason. I prayed in cathedrals around the world asking God to keep you healthy, safe, and always protected guided by music. Sinatra, my father. There is indeed a fountain of youth: it is your mind, your talents, the creativity you bring to your life and the lives of people you love. You have mastered tapping into source, you have defeated age. Age, whatever we humans define that as —you are young at heart. 

I’m so grateful for you, I’m grateful for the opportunity to love you. For this moment, this life, this experience. Grateful I am to be your daughter! I love laughing with you until our belly’s hurt, listening to classic music, art’ing at museums, cheering on the Celtics and watching you perform emanating light to people of all ages. Much of who I am is no doubt a direct reflection of you. I may have had cancer last year but at least I still had you. It was a rough year, we both learned a lot. No parent should have to see their child suffer, with God we made it through. I’m thankful to be in remission today, celebrating your monumental 75 years of life fully present with you, DaDa! You complete me. You’re my tree. You will always be my numba 1, Georgie. To a healthy, happy 200 more years of life; my sweet song bird!

It’s been a while! Recovering from 49 chemotherapy treatments has taken a toll on my bones, mental, physical and spiritual. With only luck and God’s miracles I have celebrated —one year of being in remission from Ewing’s Sarcoma Cancer! I am still adapting to life post-cancer. I am still healing. I am a perfectly imperfect flawed woman who has a strong desire to not be defeated and will to help others see their own unique light. Many wonderful moments have helped me grow immensely from the dark barren hollows of cancer. I needed to be in a quiet space and deeply reflect. I look forward to sharing some of these moments with you. Lots of love, health and strength.

What a gift it is to be alive and share this journey with the people who matter the most. Thank you for your sweet messages, they have truly brought a smile upon my face. Barbados 🇧🇧 I am in love already and it is only day one! #Virgo 🎂

Take this as your sign to book a flight! ✈️ Barbados is the 4th country I have solo traveled to. The sugar soft white sand, crystal clear waters and coconut trees provide serenity at its finest. Recovering from cancer and treatment has been taxing to say the least but I am finally feeling less pain and more freedom. I have spent over 20 hours by the sea the last 3 days just swimming! Actual paradise. 🇧🇧 🏝️

Bago Sunset 🤍
It has been a full week of travel from Boston to Panamá to Barbados to Trinidad to Tobago and now back in sweet Trinidad. From colorful sunsets to hidden lagoons and staggering lush mountains to European-inspired architecture, the Caribbean is surely one of the most beautiful places in our world!

Laguna charm in December 🌴 It is no secret that cancer uproots people from their carefully curated routinely lives, forever shifting their once premeditated path. I was diagnosed with a rare cancer, Ewing’s Sarcoma in 2021 when I was living in the vibrant coastal town of Laguna. This cancer was so rare in fact the doctors in Cali had never seen nor treated Ewing’s. Ewing’s Sarcoma is a rare type of cancerous tumor that grows in the bones or the soft tissue around the bones, such as cartilage—mine happened to be on my face. After months of misdiagnosis, a large growing mass on my left cheekbone and endless doctor appointments with no answers I had a biopsy scheduled. One week after I received the results completely clueless to what my future would soon be, packed up my life and began treatment at Dana Farber Cancer Institute @danafarber in my hometown Boston, MA. 

As tormenting as having cancer in your face and miraculously coming out alive from 49 chemotherapy treatments, 32 radiation treatments, 5 blood transfusions along with multiple surgeries there is a sense of overwhelming peace and gratitude this Cali sun brings. Your living life is a gift! You bring purpose, meaning and love to our world. Do not take for granted the importance your soul emanates. 

It is 43 degrees Fahrenheit currently in Boston, I’m soaking as much of this lovely weather up before departure. I hope you all are enjoying life in its present form through the bliss, suffering, confusion, light, color, synchronicity and laughter. Life is a complex dance of joy and sorrow that we all partake in as part of our human journey. Listen to your pain, don’t reject it. Here are some moments last week that brought me happiness!

A peaceful, prosperous and healthy Merry Christmas Eve to all ✨🎄 Sending extra love to any life that has been touched by cancer. May every innocent soul suffering at war be protected with infinite miracles. 🙏
I ❤️ New York

Two years since January 2022 when I was 4 months into a 10 month journey of chemotherapy and radiation for Ewings Sarcoma Cancer. Some weeks I had 50 hour infusions at the hospital. I’d be the first patient in around 8 am and the last patient out by 9pm. Slide 3 the red drug in a tube, doxorubicin is the most toxic chemotherapy drug. It was about to be manually administered into my blood stream through a port, which is a vein-access device that’s implanted under the skin. Manually administered because this drug is so powerful it has to be slowly injected in hopes the chemotherapy wouldn’t leak into surrounding tissues. For anyone who needs to hear this, whatever struggle you are going through be that mentally, physically, financially, or emotionally your struggles are very real however they do not define who you are. Learning is a life long enriching journey. These moments in life give us character, dimension and behemoth strength. The undying truth about life is —life will always run its own course. Much of this course we nor our egos are in control of. Low moments exist. Let your low moments talk to you and do listen carefully. I am slowly bringing back peace, strength, and patience back into my life. I know you will too.
Artist, Author, Poet, Cancer Warrior
